<section xml:id="sec-characterisations-of-invertibility-take3" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Characterisations of invertibility (take 3!)</title>

  <p> Now that we've since determinants and eigenvalues, we can add a couple more characterisations of a matrix being 
    invertible to get our final version of this theorem.
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-COI3">
<title>Characterisations of Invertibility (Part 3)</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>A</m> be an <m>n\times n</m> matrix. The following are equivalent:
<ol>
  <li>
  <p> <m>A</m> is invertible.
  </p>
  </li>
  <li>
  <p> <m>A\vect{x}=\vect{b}</m> has a unique solution for all 
  <m>\vect{x},\vect{b}\in\R^n</m>.
  </p>
  </li>
    <li>
  <p> If <m>\vect{x}\in\R^n</m> with <m>A\vect{x}=\vect{0}</m>, 
  then <m>\vect{x}=\vect{0}</m>.
  </p>
  </li>
    <li>
  <p> The RREF of <m>A</m> is <m>I_n</m>.
  </p>
  </li>
    <li>
  <p> <m>A</m> is a product of elementary matrices. 
  </p>
  </li>

  <li>
  <p> 
    <m>\operatorname{rank}(A)=n</m>.
  </p>
  </li>

  <li>
  <p> 
    <m>\operatorname{nullity}(A)=0</m>.
  </p>
  </li>

  <li>
  <p> 
    The columns of <m>A</m> are linearly independent. 
  </p>
  </li>

  <li>
  <p> 
    The columns of <m>A</m> span <m>\R^n</m>.
  </p>
  </li>

  <li>
  <p> 
    The columns of <m>A</m> are a basis for <m>\R^n</m>.
  </p>
  </li>

  <li>
  <p> 
    The rows of <m>A</m> are linearly independent. 
  </p>
  </li>

  <li>
  <p> 
    The rows of <m>A</m> span <m>\R^n</m>.
  </p>
  </li>

  <li>
  <p> 
    The rows of <m>A</m> are a basis for <m>\R^n</m>.
  </p>
  </li>

  <li>
  <p> 
    <m>\operatorname{det}(A)\not=0</m>.
  </p>
  </li>

  <li>
  <p> 
    0 is not an eigenvalue of <m>A</m>.
  </p>
  </li>

</ol>
</p>
</statement>
</theorem>

</section>